# Jupiter II

The tidal forces we discussed in the previous packet can tear an astronomical body apart if it comes too close to the primary that is causing the tidal forces. Consider again the tidal field you derived there and imagine scaling it up in strength until rocks on the near side start accelerating away from the surface because of the difference in gravitational pull while the rocks on the far side are accelerated away by the centrifugal force. You can work this out precisely, as Roche did in his derivation of the so-called **Roche radius** or **Roche limit**. The formula he found was  
	rRoche= fRoche3MmRM  	(1)

In this formula, M is the mass density of the primary, m is the density of the satellite, and RM is the radius of the primary. The coefficient fRoche varies depending on how cohesive the satellite is. If it is liquid, it will deform into an oblate spheroid, so the tidal forces on the opposite ends will be larger. Roche calculated that fRoche 2.44 for such an object. If the object is rigid, it does not deform and the tidal forces are smaller. The  fRoche=331.44.

According to [this study](https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/6a2n9ch5srbxr9a44od7a/Shoemaker-Levy9.pdf?rlkey=swucck1c1v8impen843s38j65&dl=0) of Shoemaker-Levy 9, the pre-break-up density was 500 kg/m3, and the size was estimated to be equivalent to a sphere of diameter equal to 1.4 km. 2. Metis is believed to have a density of roughly 0.86 g/cm3 . Using what you know about Jupiter’s mass and radius and the radius of Metis’ orbit, show that it is within the fluid Roche limit but just outside of the rigid Roche limit. 

3. Explain what would happen to Metis and other bodies of similar composition were they to somehow migrate to within the rigid Roche limit. Given this, what do you think lies within this region of Jupiter’s environment? 

Unsurprisingly, Jupiter, with its huge tidal forces, has a ring system with the main ring roughly inside the orbital radius of Metis. Its outer edge is at \~1.8 Jupiter radii and the ring (probably) extends inward to \~1.7 Jupiter radii where there is another ring called the halo ring. 

4. Read up on the structure of Jupiter’s rings and sketch a diagram of the rings, the Amalthea group, and the Galilean moons. Try to draw to scale, to get a sense of the relative distances involved and indicate radii in terms of Jupiter’s radii. 

Besides these satellites of Jupiter, there are very many others that are all even smaller and mostly far outside Callisto’s orbit. The current count is listed as 95 “moons”. 

### The Trojans

In this section, we will discuss the astrophysics of three bodies interacting through gravity as they co-rotate (*i.e.* all rotate around their common center of mass). Specifically, Jupiter orbits the *much* more massive Sun (by a factor \~1000) at a large distance and satellites much less massive than Jupiter orbit it at radii that are *much* less than the distance to the Sun. 

Of course we could study this system in the inertial frame of reference “looking down” on the Sun-Jupiter-satellite system from the “top” with the Sun roughly sitting still and Jupiter orbiting it (while being orbited itself by the satellite). But to understand what things look like from the point of view of someone near Jupiter, we should instead jump to the *non-inertial* frame rotating at Jupiter’s orbital speed. Recall that when we do that, Newton’s second law gets Coriolis and centrifugal corrections as in [equation 1](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1QAexguQoqmIHGKyjau8fGhDZ7XlEaB81eQJVk4Q35IU/edit?tab=t.0#bookmark=id.dchu14qwcj30) in the 5.0 Jupiter I packet. In this section, we will begin by studying the truly bizarre-looking consequences of the centrifugal term. 

Recall from the equation sheet that an object of mass m is attracted to an object of mass M a distance r away with a gravitational force given by F \= GmMr2. Here G \=6.6710-11m3kg s2 is Newton’s constant of universal gravitational strength. 

5. Consider the points on the line connecting Jupiter to the Sun. Points near the Sun are accelerated toward the Sun, whereas points near Jupiter are attracted toward Jupiter. This means that somewhere in between, the gravitational forces balance out. Use the formula above and the known values of the distances and masses to find the distance to Jupiter where these forces balance. Anywhere within a sphere of this radius is attracted to Jupiter. Anything outside of that is attracted toward the Sun. The sphere of attraction to Jupiter is called Jupiter’s **Hill sphere**. 

6. Actually, your result from the previous problem is not really correct because it assumes all the masses involved are stationary when in reality they are co-orbiting (*i.e.* orbiting around their common center of mass). In a rotating frame, there is a centrifugal term that we get in a frame that is rotating with Jupiter’s orbital rotation rate . This is the third term in [equation 1](#bookmark=id.dchu14qwcj30) above. Using the orbital period equation from the [equation sheet](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1x1mI-sdzAxJFSf8ZZbeYfI_a9FznPwg2NDIp6_5cJR4/edit), confirm that for the angular revolution rate of Jupiter 2=2 P2=GMd3, where d is the distance between Jupiter and the Sun. Argue that this means that the term we need to add has a magnitude of GmMd3r.

The effects of the orbital term are far more interesting than you might at first think. Firstly, the radius of Jupiter’s Hill sphere is shifted to 

	rHill= 3MJ3M d	(3)

where d is Jupiter’s orbital radius. The point between Jupiter and the Sun at this distance from Jupiter is where the forces balance. This point is called the first Lagrange point L1. 

More interestingly, there is another point on the other side of Jupiter where the centrifugal term is balanced by the inward gravitational forces of Jupiter and the Sun combined. This one is called L2. You can calculate that this is again at a distance given by the Hill radius. 

But wait\! There’s more\!

On the other side of the Sun just outside of Jupiter’s orbit the centrifugal force is balanced by the inward gravitational force of Jupiter and the Sun combined. This one is called L3. These three Lagrange points are schematically represented by the following diagram:

![][image1]

But wait\! There’s more\! 

For reasons I’ll only go into if you ask, there are two more Lagrange points called L4 and L5. They are located at the third vertex of equilateral triangles formed with the primary and secondary as a base.

7. Draw a to-scale diagram (either using a program or by hand) of the primary (Sun) and secondary (Jupiter) that has all five Lagrange points labeled. (The Sun and Jupiter can be taken to be points, but the distances should be to scale.) The Lagrange point L4 is the one ahead of Jupiter in the orbit and L5 is the trailing point.

A useful visual device is called an “potential energy surface”.  In physics we learn that we can associate an energy to the gravitational interaction and write a potential energy function for gravity. When there is more than one gravitating object, you simply add all their potential energy functions together. If you plot the surface, higher points correspond to places of higher gravitational energy and lower points correspond to lower energy. Maxima and minima of the surface correspond to points where the forces are balanced. Because of this, the energy surface gives a visual representation of how the forces act at all points in space. For Jupiter’s orbit of the Sun the effective gravitational potential energy is schematically of the form

(4)	u \= \- 1a \- mb \- r2

where r is the radial distance from the Sun and m=M♃M☉ is the ratio of Jupiter’s mass to the Sun’s. The a and b are functions of the radius and the angle  in the plane from the line connecting Jupiter to the Sun. Explicitly a=  m2+r2 \+2rm   and b= 1+r2 \-2r  .

Usually, only the minima of a potential surface are stable points: When you move away from them, the potential energy goes up, so you need energy to get away from such a point. However, we must remember that in a rotating frame of reference there is also a Coriolis effect to consider. 

11. Consider an object “rolling down the hill” starting from L4. This gives a velocity vector to this object. Use the right-hand rule and the Coriolis term in equation (1) of the previous packet to find the direction of acceleration the object will experience. Use this understanding to explain what is happening in [this animation](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9ltz2AvT-Gs). 

This exercise shows that the Lagrange points L4 and L5 are “stable”. The quotes serve to remind us that this is not your usual stability where you poke something and it oscillates. Nevertheless, objects that end up near these points tend to stay close to these points, so you should not be surprised to find out that there are large groups of asteroids near the L4 and L5 Sun-Jupiter Lagrange points. The first such asteroid discovered was named [588 Achilles](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/588_Achilles) near L4. Because of this, the collection became known as the [Trojan asteroids](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jupiter_trojan). The group near L4 is known as the Greek camp and the group near L5 makes up the Trojan camp.

# An Aside on Atmospheres

Some planets and moons have thick atmospheres whereas others have very thin ones. What determines whether a body retains an atmosphere and what can we expect of the composition if it does? 

14. Play with the buttons and sliders on [this simulation](http://www.falstad.com/gas/gas.html) and report back on what you observe. 

You may have learned in chemistry about the equipartition of energy. It takes some statistical physics to formulate precisely and prove, but it basically says that for every dimension available to it, a particle in an ideal gas at temperature T has an average kinetic energy of 12kBT where kB1.38 10-23 J/K is Boltzmann’s constant. It is related to the ideal gas constant by R=kB NA where NA is Avogadro’s number. 

15. In physics, we learn about the kinetic energy K=12mv2 of a particle. Use the fact that we live in three dimensions to show that the average speed vave of a molecule of mass m is vave=3kBTm. Write this in terms of the molar mass[^1] \=mmp where mp is the mass of the proton, and plug in the numbers to show that 

	vave157T	  
	  
in m/s where T is in Kelvin.

Whether a body retains an atmosphere is determined by whether there is a sufficient gravitational attraction of the gas to the surface.

16. Reason qualitatively to explain why an atmosphere is not retained if the temperature of the gas is too high. Explain what you expect of the composition of the gas by considering the role of the molar mass. What quantitative calculation could you do to check your reasoning?

The molecules that make up the gas do not all have the average speed you calculated above. The distribution of speeds in an ideal gas is called the Maxwell velocity distribution. It is of the form f(v)=a32 v2 e-av2, where aT.

17. Plot this velocity distribution on Desmos with a slider for a. (Multiply the overall distribution by 10 or so to get it to look bigger.) Play with the slider and explain what happens to the distribution as you change the temperature and mass.

You can see from the Maxwell distribution that there are molecules in the gas with speeds much higher than the average velocity. In fact, there is always a small but non-zero fraction of the molecules that have speeds higher than the escape speed for that astronomical body. When these molecules escape into space, the continual random collisions of the remaining gas replenishes this high-speed “tail” of the distribution by giving some molecules that had lower speeds higher speed. This process will continue as long as the temperature of the gas is not lowered, so any atmosphere will gradually leak into space. How long it takes for a substantial part of the atmosphere to escape in this way depends only on the ratio between the average molecular speed (so temperature and molar mass) and escape speed (so mass of and radius of astronomical body). For an atmosphere to stick around for billions of years, the rule of thumb is that vave should be at least a factor of 6 smaller than vesc. 

18. Convert the escape velocity formula to a more useful form by showing that it is equivalent to vesc=11,200 MR in m/s where M is the mass in Earth masses and R is the radius in Earth radii. Use this to show that molecular hydrogen may be expected to leak out of our atmosphere over time, whereas nitrogen or oxygen will not. Check that it makes sense that Jupiter would have a thick atmosphere of hydrogen and helium.
